10 Oct 2016

Smoothing again

Gaussian processes

Suppose that \(X = X_{1:n} \sim \mathcal{N}(\xi_x, \Sigma_{x})\) with \[\mathrm{cov}(X_i, X_j) = K(t_i - t_j)\] for a kernel function \(K\).

With the observation equation \(Y_i = X_i + \delta_i\) for \(\delta = \delta_{1:n} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \Omega)\) and \(\delta \perp \! \! \perp X\) we get \[(X, Y) \sim \mathcal{N}\left(\left(\begin{array}{c} \xi_x \\ \xi_x \end{array}\right), \left(\begin{array}{cc} \Sigma_x & \Sigma_x \\ \Sigma_x & \Sigma_x + \Omega \end{array} \right) \right).\]

Hence \[E(X \mid Y) = \xi_x + \Sigma_x (\Sigma_x + \Omega)^{-1} (Y - \xi_x).\]

Gaussian processes and smoothing

Assuming that \(\xi_x = 0\) the conditional expectation is a linear smoother with smoother matrix \[S = \Sigma_x (\Sigma_x + \Omega)^{-1}.\]

This is also true if \(\Sigma_x (\Sigma_x + \Omega)^{-1} \xi_x = \xi_x\). If this identity holds approximately, we can argue that for computing \(E(X \mid Y)\) we don't need to know \(\xi_x\).

If the observation variance is \(\Omega = \sigma^2 I\) then the smoother matrix is \[\Sigma_x (\Sigma_x + \sigma^2 I)^{-1} = (I + \sigma^2 \Sigma_x^{-1})^{-1}.\]

The Kalman filter and smoother

Suppose that \(|\alpha| < 1\), \(X_1 = \epsilon_1 / \sqrt{1 - \alpha^2}\) and \[X_i = \alpha X_{i-1} + \epsilon_i\] for \(i = 2, \ldots, n\) with \(\epsilon = \epsilon_{1:n} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I)\).

Then the computation of \(E(X_n \mid Y)\) is a filtering problem for a hidden Markov model that fits into the sequential Monte Carlo framework.

But we also have \(\mathrm{cov}(X_i, X_j) = \alpha^{|i-j|} / (1 - \alpha^2)\), thus we can find \(\Sigma_x\) and compute \[E(X_n \mid Y) = ((I + \sigma^2 \Sigma_x^{-1})^{-1} Y)_n\]

The main point

Observe that \[\Sigma_x^{-1} = \left( \begin{array}{cccccc} 1 & -\alpha & 0 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ -\alpha & 1 + \alpha^2 & -\alpha & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & -\alpha & 1 + \alpha^2 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & 1 + \alpha^2 & -\alpha \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & -\alpha & 1 \\ \end{array}\right).\]

Derivation

This can be derived from observing that \(\epsilon = A X\) where

\[A = \left( \begin{array}{cccccc} \sqrt{1 - \alpha^2} & 0 & 0 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ -\alpha & 1 & 0 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & -\alpha & 1 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & -\alpha & 1 \\ \end{array}\right),\]

which follows from the identity \(\epsilon_i = X_i - \alpha X_{i-1}\). This gives \(I = V(\epsilon) = A \Sigma_x A^T\), hence \[\Sigma_x^{-1} = (A^{-1}(A^T)^{-1})^{-1} = A^T A.\]

The main point

Hence \[I + \sigma^2 \Sigma_x^{-1} = \left( \begin{array}{cccccc} \gamma_0 & \rho & 0 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ \rho & \gamma & \rho & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & \rho & \gamma & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & \gamma & \rho \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & \rho & \gamma_0 \\ \end{array}\right)\]

with \(\gamma_0 = 1 + \sigma^2\), \(\gamma = 1 + \sigma^2 (1 + \alpha^2)\) and \(\rho = -\sigma^2 \alpha\) is a tridiagonal matrix.

Solving an equation

The equation

\[\left( \begin{array}{cccccc} \gamma_0 & \rho & 0 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ \rho & \gamma & \rho & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & \rho & \gamma & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & \gamma & \rho \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & \rho & \gamma_0 \\ \end{array}\right) \left( \begin{array}{c} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3 \\ \vdots \\ x_{n-1} \\ x_n \end{array}\right) = \left(\begin{array}{c} y_1 \\ y_2 \\ y_3 \\ \vdots \\ y_{n-1} \\ y_n \end{array}\right)\]

can be solved by a forward and backward sweep.

Forward sweep

Set \(\rho_1' = \rho / \gamma_0\) and \(y_1' = y_1 / \gamma_0\),

then recursively \[\rho_i' = \frac{\rho}{\gamma - \rho \rho_{i-1}'} \quad \text{and} \quad y_i' = \frac{y_i - \rho y_{i-1}'}{\gamma - \rho \rho_{i-1}'}\] for \(i = 2, \ldots, n-1\)

and finally \[y_n' = \frac{y_n - \rho y_{n-1}'}{\gamma_0 - \rho \rho_{n-1}'}.\]

Forward sweep result

By the forward sweep the equation is transformed to

\[\left( \begin{array}{cccccc} 1 & \rho_1' & 0 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 & \rho_2' & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 & \ldots & 0 & 0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots & \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & 1 & \rho_{n-1}' \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \ldots & 0 & 1 \\ \end{array}\right) \left( \begin{array}{c} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3 \\ \vdots \\ x_{n-1} \\ x_n \end{array}\right) = \left(\begin{array}{c} y_1' \\ y_2' \\ y_3' \\ \vdots \\ y_{n-1}' \\ y_n' \end{array}\right),\]

which is then solved by backsubstitution from below; \(x_n = y_n'\) and \[x_{i} = y_i' - \rho_{i}' x_{i+1}, \quad i = n-1, \ldots, 1.\]

Implementation

cppFunction(
  'NumericVector KalmanSmooth(NumericVector y, double alpha, double sigmasq) {
  double tmp, gamma0 = 1 + sigmasq, rho = - sigmasq * alpha;
  double gamma = 1 + sigmasq * (1 + alpha * alpha);
  int n = y.size();
  NumericVector x(n), rhop(n - 1);
  rhop[0] = rho / gamma0;
  x[0] = y[0] / gamma0;
  for(int i = 1; i < n - 1; ++i) { /* Forward sweep */
    tmp = (gamma - rho * rhop[i - 1]);
    rhop[i] = rho / tmp;
    x[i] = (y[i] - rho * x[i - 1]) / tmp;
  }
  x[n - 1] = (y[n - 1] - rho * x[n - 2]) / (gamma0 - rho * rhop[n - 2]);
  for(int i = n - 2; i >= 0; --i) { /* Backsubstitution */
    x[i] = x[i] - rhop[i] * x[i + 1];
  }
  return x;
  }')

Result, \(\alpha = 0.95\), \(\sigma^2 = 10\)

Comparing results

n <- 200; alpha <- 0.95; sigmasq <- 10
Sigma <- outer(1:n, 1:n, 
               function(i, j) alpha^(abs(i - j))) / (1 - alpha^2)

The Kalman smoother

Note that the forward sweep only computes \(x_n = E(X_n \mid Y)\), and thus solves the filtration problem. From this, the backsubstitution solves the smoothing problem of computing \(E(X \mid Y)\).

The Gaussian process used here (the AR(1)-process) is not very smooth and nor is the smooth of the data. This is related to the kernel function \(K(s) = \alpha^{|s|}\) being non-differentiable in 0.

Many smoothers are equivalent to a Gaussian process smoother with an appropriate choice of kernel. Not all have a simple inverse covariance matrix and a Kalman filter algorithm.

The Kalman filter only (forward sweep)

cppFunction(
  'NumericVector KalmanFilt(NumericVector y, double alpha, double sigmasq) {
  double tmp, gamma0 = 1 + sigmasq, rho = - sigmasq * alpha, yp;
  double gamma = 1 + sigmasq * (1 + alpha * alpha);
  int n = y.size();
  NumericVector x(n), rhop(n);
  rhop[0] = rho / gamma0;
  yp = y[0] / gamma0;
  x[0] = y[0] / (1 + sigmasq * (1 - alpha * alpha));
  for(int i = 1; i < n; ++i) { 
    tmp = (gamma - rho * rhop[i - 1]);
    rhop[i] = rho / tmp;
    /* Note differences when compared to smoother */
    x[i] = (y[i] - rho * yp) / (gamma0 - rho * rhop[i - 1]); 
    yp = (y[i] - rho * yp) / tmp;         
  }
  return x;
  }')

Result, \(\alpha = 0.95\), \(\sigma^2 = 10\)

Sequential MC for the AR(1)-process

Recall the update equation \[X_{t} = \alpha X_{t-1} + \epsilon_t.\] and the observation equation \[Y_t = X_t + \delta_t.\]

Simulating a sample path

simAR <- function(t, alpha) {
  x <- numeric(t)
  e <- rnorm(t, 0, 1)
  x[1] <- e[1] / sqrt(1 - alpha^2)
  for(s in seq_len(t)[-1]) {
    x[s] <- alpha * x[s - 1] + e[s]
  }
  x
}

Simulating a sample path

We first generate a realization from the process with \(\alpha = 0.9\) and observation variance \(\sigma^2 = 10\).

Bootstrap filter

bootAR <- function(y, n, alpha, sigma){
  t <- length(y)
  x <- xre <- matrix(0, n, t)
  u <- matrix(0, n, t)
  e <- matrix(rnorm(n * t, 0, 1), n, t)
  x[, 1] <- e[, 1] / sqrt(1 - alpha^2)
  for(s in seq_len(t - 1)) {
    u[, s] <- dnorm(y[s], x[, s], sigma)
    resamp <- sample(n, n, replace = TRUE, prob = u[, s])
    x[, s + 1] <- alpha * x[resamp, s] + e[, s + 1]
  }
  u[, t] <- dnorm(y[t], x[, t], sigma)
  list(x = x, u = u)
}

Filtering with 10 particles

set.seed(10102016)
n <- 10
bootFilt <- bootAR(y, n, alpha, sigma)
xBootFilt <- colSums(bootFilt$x * bootFilt$u) / colSums(bootFilt$u)

Rcpp implementation

Rcpp comparison

The two implementations do, in fact, compute the same if they are started as above with the same seed.

max(abs(xBootFilt2 - xBootFilt))
[1] 8.881784e-16

Conditional expectations from the bootstrap filter converges for \(n \to \infty\) toward the Kalman filter. The bootstrap filter is a general algorithm whereas the Kalman filter is specific to Gaussian and linear processes.

Benchmarking

The Kalman filter is blazingly fast, while the Rcpp version of the bootstrap filter is not even a factor two faster than the pure R implementation.

Summary

  • The Kalman filter and Kalman smoother are ideal for implementation using Rcpp. Though no R implementation was made for comparison, it is likely to be somewhat slower.

  • The bootstrap filter could be conveniently implemented in R. The loop is over the observations, while all particles are handled in a vectorized way.

  • The Rcpp implementation is longer, and sample is not directly available. Instead, sampling is performed using a function from RcppArmadillo (another R package).

  • I suspect the sample function used via Rcpp is a bottleneck. Sampling from a very large number of items is, in fact, not entirely trivial to do fastly.
